If `ng.probe` returns null, that's likely because the Angular application is running in production mode, which disables the Angular debug tools for performance and security reasons. In this case, you may try the following alternative approach:

1. Temporarily enable debug tools in the Angular application: 

Add the following line of code to the `main.ts` file of your Angular application to enable debug tools:

```javascript
import { enableProdMode } from '@angular/core';
// ...
if (environment.production) {
  enableProdMode();
} else {
  // Add this line to enable debug tools in non-production mode.
  window['ngDevMode'] = true;
}
```

Then, rebuild and redeploy your application to enable the debug tools in the non-production environment. Note, however, that this can have performance and security implications, so it should not be used in a production environment.

2. Accessing component data using the ElementRef and ViewChild decorator (only applicable when you have access to the source code):

If you have access to the source code of the application, you can create a ViewChild decorator to access a specific element and then modify the associated form data. Here's an example of how to use ElementRef and ViewChild:

inside `component.html`

```html
<input #myInput type="text" [(ngModel)]="myText">
```

inside `component.ts`

```typescript
import { ElementRef, ViewChild } from '@angular/core';

// ...

export class AppComponent {
  @ViewChild('myInput', { static: false }) myInput: ElementRef;

  // ...
}
```

The ElementRef is now accessible within the `AppComponent` class, allowing you to modify the form data by accessing the `nativeElement` property of the ElementRef.

```typescript
editInput() {
  this.myInput.nativeElement.value = 'new value';
}
```

Remember that the above methods should be used with caution as they can potentially expose sensitive application information or introduce performance issues. Always make sure to disable Angular debug tools in production environments.

If `ng.probe($0)` is not working and you don't have access to the source code, you can still try to manipulate the private value in an Angular app. One way to do this is by injecting javascript code directly into the Angular app to expose the component instance.

Please note that the following method is a hacky workaround and should not be used in production environments.

Follow these steps to change the private Angular component value:

1. Add a bookmark in your browser with the following code as the URL (This will create a bookmarklet that you can click on any Angular page):

```javascript
javascript:(function() { 
  var script = document.createElement('script');
  script.src = "https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/angular.js/1.2.1/angular.min.js";
  script.onload = function() {
    var elements = document.getElementsByTagName('*');
    for(var i = 0; i < elements.length; i++) {
      var el = elements[i];
      var ngComponent = el.getAttribute('ng-component');            
      if(ngComponent) {
          el.setAttribute('id', ngComponent);
            el.onclick = function() {
              alert('You have selected the "' + this.getAttribute('id') + '" component. Open your dev tools console for more information.');
              console.log("_SELECTED_COMPONENT: ");
              console.log(ng.probe(this));
            };
        }
    }
};
document.head.appendChild(script);
})()
```

2. Load the Angular page you want to test.

3. Click on the bookmark you created previously to execute the script. It will add all available Angular components to the console.

4. Click on the component you want to change, and an alert message will show informing you that the component is selected.

5. Open the browser's Developer Tools, and you will see the message "_SELECTED_COMPONENT:" printed out with the DebugElement containing the component instance.

6. In the Developer Tools Console, type the following command to assign the selected component to a global variable:
```javascript
const componentInstance = _SELECTED_COMPONENT.componentInstance;
```

7. Now, with the `componentInstance` variable, you can access any public or private properties or methods of the Angular component and make any changes you want:
```javascript
componentInstance.privateValue = 'newValue';
```

Again, please note that this method should not be used in production environments as it could potentially introduce security and stability issues.
